The question seems to be asking about the concept Fred Dretske used the zebra/mule example to illustrate, which is most commonly associated with his **"relative alternatives theory of knowledge"** (or **knowledge as justified true belief with respect to alternatives**).

\boxed{relative alternatives theory of knowledge}

Dretske’s example (a zebra appearing as a mule) highlights how knowledge depends on the *relevant alternatives*—what one could reasonably have believed instead. This challenges the traditional Gettier problem by emphasizing the role of alternatives in defining knowledge.
